          "body": "The chapter opens with a speech by a Speaker who commands the Gentile coastlands to listen — an extraordinary claim for a private individual. He identifies Himself in terms that echo Jeremiah's prophetic call (Jer. 1:5): named from the womb, formed before birth. His equipment is verbal: a mouth like a sharp sword, a body like a polished arrow. Both images are instruments of God's word, not of military force. The sword-mouth anticipates the New Testament's description of the risen Christ (Rev. 1:16; 19:15) and of Scripture itself (Heb. 4:12). But before the equipment is deployed, it is hidden — in the shadow of God's hand, in His quiver. Concealment precedes commission; the Servant's readiness is maintained while God's timing is awaited.\n\nVerse 4 is the emotional center of the opening: 'I have toiled in vain, I have spent My strength for nothing and vanity.' The language is total — not partial effort but exhausted output, not partial disappointment but tohu and hevel, the void-and-breath vocabulary of Ecclesiastes. The Servant has given everything and received nothing visible in return. The complaint is not faithlessness; it is radical honesty. And it is followed immediately by faith's pivot: 'Yet surely the justice due to Me is with the LORD.' The akhen — 'yet surely' — is the hinge on which the whole chapter turns. The Servant grounds His confidence not in evidence but in the character of God as righteous Judge."
