          "body": "The chapter's most human moment arrives immediately after creation's praise: 'But Zion said, the LORD has forsaken me, and the LORD has forgotten me' (49:14). The juxtaposition is not accidental. The prophet captures with pastoral precision the distance between theological truth (God has acted, creation praises) and existential experience (I feel abandoned). Zion is not rebuked for the feeling; she is answered.\n\nGod's answer moves through three escalating arguments. First, an analogy: can a woman forget her nursing child? The nursing bond is biology and emotion fused — among the most powerful attachments in human experience. The LORD uses it as the nearest human approximation to His own attachment to Zion. Second, a concession: even she may forget — human love, however powerful, has limits and can fail. Third, the counter: 'But I will not forget you.' The divine 'but' (akhen-equivalent) is the chapter's deepest theological note: God's love for Zion is categorically more reliable than the most powerful human love we know.\n\nVerse 16 provides the image: 'I have inscribed you on the palms of My hands.' The Hebrew chaqaq (to engrave, to incise) suggests permanent inscription, not a written note that can be lost. The image is intimate and irreversible. Zion's walls — the very ruins that signal her desolation — are 'continually before Me' (tamid). The desolation is not absence from God's sight; it is a wound He sees at all times. Calvin notes that this is the strongest possible answer to unbelief: God does not merely remember Israel from afar; He carries the evidence of her in His own hands."
