          "body": "Having answered Zion's theology of abandonment with the engraved-palms image, the LORD turns to the demographic reversal. The builders hurry back; the destroyers depart. Zion is commanded to lift her eyes and look around: 'All of them gather together, they come to you.' The oath formula 'As I live, declares the LORD' underscores that what follows is backed by the divine life itself. Zion will wear the returning exiles as bridal jewelry — the image transforms refugees into adornment, loss into abundance.\n\nVerses 19-21 develop the reversal with domestic pathos. The land that was 'too cramped' in oppression (the destroyers took all the space) will be 'too cramped' in restoration — but now because there are too many people, not too few. The children born in exile will crowd back to a mother who thought herself barren, bereaved, and alone. Zion's internal monologue in verse 21 — 'Who has begotten these for me? Who has reared these?' — captures the disorientation of grace: the restoration exceeds what the recipient imagined possible.\n\nVerses 22-23 name the instrument of this reversal: the nations. The LORD lifts His hand and sets His standard — military language for a victorious command — and the Gentile nations respond by bringing Israel's sons in their arms and daughters on their shoulders. Kings become guardians; queens become nurses. Those who bowed Zion down will bow to the dust of her feet. The purpose clause lands: 'Then you will know that I am the LORD; those who hopefully wait for Me will not be put to shame.' The whole reversal is epistemological as well as historical — it produces knowledge of God's identity and vindicates the posture of patient, covenant-confident waiting."
